#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:5
msgid "F2PY and Windows"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:9
msgid "F2PY support for Windows is not always at par with Linux support"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:12
msgid ""
"`SciPy's documentation`_ has some information on system-level dependencies "
"which are well tested for Fortran as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:15
msgid "Broadly speaking, there are two issues working with F2PY on Windows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:17
msgid "the lack of actively developed FOSS Fortran compilers, and,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:18
msgid ""
"the linking issues related to the C runtime library for building Python-C "
"extensions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:20
msgid ""
"The focus of this section is to establish a guideline for developing and "
"extending Fortran modules for Python natively, via F2PY on Windows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:23
msgid "Currently supported toolchains are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:25
msgid "Mingw-w64 C/C++/Fortran compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:26
msgid "Intel compilers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:27
msgid "Clang-cl + Flang"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:28
msgid "MSVC + Flang"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:31
msgid "Overview"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:33
msgid ""
"From a user perspective, the most UNIX compatible Windows development "
"environment is through emulation, either via the Windows Subsystem on Linux, "
"or facilitated by Docker. In a similar vein, traditional virtualization "
"methods like VirtualBox are also reasonable methods to develop UNIX tools on "
"Windows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:39
msgid ""
"Native Windows support is typically stunted beyond the usage of commercial "
"compilers. However, as of 2022, most commercial compilers have free plans "
"which are sufficient for general use. Additionally, the Fortran language "
"features supported by ``f2py`` (partial coverage of Fortran 2003), means "
"that newer toolchains are often not required. Briefly, then, for an end "
"user, in order of use:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:50
msgid "Classic Intel Compilers (commercial)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:46
msgid ""
"These are maintained actively, though licensing restrictions may apply as "
"further detailed in :ref:`f2py-win-intel`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:49
msgid ""
"Suitable for general use for those building native Windows programs by "
"building off of MSVC."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:54
msgid "MSYS2 (FOSS)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:53
msgid ""
"In conjunction with the ``mingw-w64`` project, ``gfortran`` and ``gcc`` "
"toolchains can be used to natively build Windows programs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:58
msgid "Windows Subsystem for Linux"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:57
msgid ""
"Assuming the usage of ``gfortran``, this can be used for cross-compiling "
"Windows applications, but is significantly more complicated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:61
msgid "Conda"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:61
msgid ""
"Windows support for GNU compilers in ``conda`` is provided by `conda-forge`_ "
"channel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:66
msgid "PGI Compilers (commercial)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:64
msgid ""
"Unmaintained but sufficient if an existing license is present. Works "
"natively, but has been superseded by the Nvidia HPC SDK, with no `native "
"Windows support`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:71
msgid "Cygwin (FOSS)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:69
msgid ""
"Can also be used for ``gfortran``. However, the POSIX API compatibility "
"layer provided by Cygwin is meant to compile UNIX software on Windows, "
"instead of building native Windows programs. This means cross compilation is "
"required."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:75
msgid "Intel oneAPI"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:74
msgid ""
"The newer Intel compilers (``ifx``, ``icx``) are based on LLVM and can be "
"used for native compilation. Licensing requirements can be onerous."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:80
msgid "Classic Flang (FOSS)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:78
msgid ""
"The backbone of the PGI compilers were cannibalized to form the \"classic\" "
"or `legacy version of Flang`_. This may be compiled from source and used "
"natively. `LLVM Flang`_ does not support Windows yet (30-01-2022)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:85
msgid "LFortran (FOSS)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../f2py/windows/index.rst:83
msgid ""
"One of two LLVM based compilers. Not all of F2PY supported Fortran can be "
"compiled yet (30-01-2022) but uses MSVC for native linking."
msgstr ""

